The ''[[Bureau d'Enquêtes et d'Analyses pour la Sécurité de l'Aviation Civile]]'' (BEA) opened an investigation into the crash, joined by its German counterpart, the [[German Federal Bureau of Aircraft Accidents Investigation|Federal Bureau of Aircraft Accidents Investigation]] (BFU), and assisted by the U.S. [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/videos/us/2015/03/26/lead-brown-fbi-investigation-germanwings-crash.cnn|title=FBI assisting in crash investigation|date=26 March 2015|publisher=CNN|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Germanwings Flight 9525 co-pilot deliberately crashed plane, officials say|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/03/26/europe/france-germanwings-plane-crash-main/|website=CNN}}</ref> On 24 March, the BEA sent seven investigators to the crash site, accompanied by representatives from [[Airbus]] and [[CFM International]]. The BEA held a press conference on 25 March from 16:00 to 16:45 UTC.<ref>{{cite web|title= Accident to the Airbus A320-211 registered D-AIPX, flight GWI18G, on 24 March 2015|url=http://www.bea.aero/en/enquetes/flight.gwi18g/flight.gwi18g.php|publisher=Bureau d'Enquêtes et d'Analyses pour la Sécurité de l'Aviation Civile|accessdate=24 March 2015|language=French|date=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aviationtribune.com/safety/item/2156-germanwings-flight-4u9525-crashes-in-french-alps |accessdate=25 March 2015 |date=24 March 2015 |title=Germanwings flight 4U9525 crashes in French Alps (updated) |work=Aviation Tribune}}</ref>

The [[cockpit voice recorder]] was recovered by rescue workers and was examined by the investigation team.<ref name="rt.c_Germ">{{cite web| title = Germanwings A320 black box found in French Alps| publisher = [[RT (TV network)|RT]]| date = 24 March 2015| accessdate = 24 March 2015| url = http://rt.com/news/243669-germanwings-flight-recorder-found/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Germanwings plane black box found as investigators reach crash site |work=The Guardian |url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/mar/24/germanwings-plane-black-box-found-as-investigators-reach-crash-site |date=24 March 2015 |accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> The recorder was damaged in the crash, but was still in a usable condition.<ref name="foxnews.com"/> The BEA released photos of the CVR<ref name=BEA>{{cite web |url=http://www.bea.aero/fr/enquetes/vol.gwi18g/mediatheque.php |title=Accident d'un Airbus A 320-211 immatriculé D-AIPX, vol GWI18G, survenu le 24 mars 2015 |publisher=BEA |language=fr |accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref> and was able to extract a voice recording.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/25/us-france-crash-investigation-idUSKBN0ML1Y320150325 |title=Useable voice recording recovered from Alps crash: investigators |date=25 March 2015 |accessdate=25 March 2015 |agency=Reuters |first=Tim |last=Hepher |location=Paris}}</ref>

The French prosecutor, the French and German authorities, and a spokesperson for Germanwings all stated that the crash was intentional.<ref name="nytimes1">{{cite news|last1=Clark|first1=Nicola|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan|title=Germanwings Co-Pilot Deliberately Crashed Airbus Jet, French Prosecutor Says|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/27/world/europe/germanwings-crash.html|accessdate=26 March 2015|work=The New York Times|date=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref name="guardianpress">{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2015/mar/26/germanwings-plane-crash-investigation-press-conference-live-updates-4u9525|title=Germanwings Plane Crash Investigation|date=26 March 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref name="CBC1">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/germanwings-flight-4u9525-co-pilot-put-plane-into-descent-prosecutor-says-1.3010045|title=Germanwings Flight 4U9525: Co-pilot put plane into descent, prosecutor says|date=26 March 2015|work=[[CBC News]]|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref name="CNN1">{{cite news|last1=Levs|first1=Josh|last2=Smith-Spark|first2=Laura|last3=Yan|first3=Holly|title=Germanwings Flight 9525 co-pilot deliberately crashed plane, officials say|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/03/26/europe/france-germanwings-plane-crash-main/index.html|accessdate=26 March 2015|work=CNN|date=26 March 2015}}</ref> Lufthansa CEO Carsten Spohr stated that the pilot returned to the cabin from a toilet break and entered his code to open the cockpit door, but co-pilot Andreas Lubitz, a 27-year-old German citizen, had disabled access from the cockpit controls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2015/mar/26/germanwings-plane-crash-investigation-press-conference-live-updates-4u9525|title=Germanwings crash: 'co-pilot's actions leave us speechless,' says airline|work=The Guardian|date=27 March 2015}}</ref> The pilot then banged on the door, with no response from the co-pilot.<ref name=Clark/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.yahoo.com/pilot-locked-cockpit-germanwings-crash-source-022140232.html|title=Pilot locked out of cockpit before mystery French Alps crash|date=26 March 2015|work=Yahoo News|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-26/germanwings-pilot-outside-cockpit-before-crash-report/6349546|title=Germanwings plane crash: Pilot locked out of cockpit before aircraft hit French Alps, says investigator, German state prosecutor|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=25 March 2015}}</ref> Transponder data show the autopilot had switched from the cruising altitude of {{convert|38000|ft|m}} to {{convert|100|ft|m}}, which is the lowest setting for the autopilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/26/us-france-crash-idUSKBN0MK2U020150326|title=German police search house of pilot who flew A320 into mountain|date=26 March 2015|accessdate=26 March 2015|work=Reuters|author=Tim Hepher}}</ref> During the descent, the co-pilot did not respond to questions from air traffic control and did not transmit a distress call. [[Marseille]] prosecutor Brice Robin said that contact from the Marseille air traffic control tower was audible on the [[cockpit voice recorder]] multiple times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-26/germanwings-co-pilot-crashed-plane-deliberately-prosecutor-says/6351854|title=Germanwings plane crash: Co-pilot of flight appears to have crashed plane deliberately, French prosecutor says|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=27 March 2015}}</ref>

<!--If the Media Leak section header is reinstated, please place this above the header-->On 26 March, Marseille prosecutor Brice Robin said it appeared that co-pilot Lubitz, a 27-year-old German, crashed the jet deliberately.<ref name="nytimes1"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hepher|first1=Tim|last2=Rosnoblet|first2=Jean-Francois||title=Co-pilot appears to have crashed Germanwings plane deliberately: French prosecutor|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/26/us-france-crash-idUSKBN0MK2U020150326|accessdate=26 March 2015|agency=Reuters|date=26 March 2015}}</ref>

Marseille prosecutor Robin said that the co-pilot Lubitz's responses, initially courteous in the first part of the trip, became "curt" when the captain began the mid-flight briefing on the planned landing. Lubitz is thought to have manually set the plane on the descent that drove it into the mountain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/alone-at-controls-co-pilot-sought-to-destroy-the-plane/ar-AAa1d9O?ocid=ASUDHP|title=Alone at controls, co-pilot sought to 'destroy' the plane|first1=Lori|last1=Hinnant|first2=Dave|last2=McHugh|date=26 March 2015|accessdate=26 March 2015|publisher=MSN}}</ref> The screams of passengers can be heard on the voice recorder in the final seconds before impact.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/germanwings-plane-crash-passengers-screamed-5404304|title=Germanwings plane crash: Passengers screamed in horror seconds before jet was deliberately crashed into Alps at 430mph|first1=Anthony|last1=Bond|first2=Dan|last2=Bloom|date=26 March 2015|accessdate=26 March 2015|publisher=[[Daily Mirror]]}}</ref>

Police searched Lubitz's home for evidence,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-32063587|title=Germanwings plane crash: Co-pilot 'wanted to destroy plane'|publisher=BBC News|date=26 March 2015|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref> including religious ties. However, Marseille prosecutor Robin responded to a reporter's question about Lubitz's religious background by stating, "I don't think that's where the answer to this lies".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/andreas-lubitz-religion-debate-germanwings-crash-raises-questions-over-pilots-faith-1860396|title=Andreas Lubitz Religion Debate: Germanwings Crash Raises Questions Over Pilot's Faith|date=26 March 2015|work=International Business Times|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>

==Response==
===Political===
<!-- Please see [[WP:OVERQUOTE]] before adding any condolence quotes to this section! -->
French [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minister of the Interior]] [[Bernard Cazeneuve]] remarked that due to the "violence of the impact" there was "little hope" that any survivors would be found.<ref name="National Post">{{cite news |title='The plane is disintegrated': 150 dead as Airbus A320 goes down in Southern France |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2015/03/24/survivors-unlikely-after-airbus-carrying-148-passengers-crashes-in-southern-france/ |newspaper=[[National Post]] |location=[[Toronto]], Canada |date=24 March 2015 |accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Manuel Valls]] dispatched Interior Minister Cazeneuve to the scene and set-up a ministerial crisis cell to co-ordinate the response to the incident.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|title=Germanwings airliner crashes in French Alps|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-32030270|accessdate=24 March 2015|publisher=BBC News|date=24 March 2015}}</ref>

[[Monarchy of Spain|King]] [[Felipe VI of Spain|Felipe VI]] of Spain, in Paris for a [[state visit]] to France at the time of the crash, cut his visit short and returned to Spain.<ref name="BBC live"/>

German [[Chancellor of Germany|Chancellor]] [[Angela Merkel]] traveled to the crash site on 25 March together with [[Minister-President#Germany|Minister-President]] of North Rhine-Westphalia [[Hannelore Kraft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2015-03-24/angela-merkel-to-travel-to-germanwings-crash-site/ |title=Angela Merkel to travel to Germanwings crash site |publisher=ITV News |date=24 March 2015 |accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref name="edit_Fren">{{cite web| title = France crash: Germanwings plane obliterated, data recorder found| last = Botelho | first = Greg| last2 = Smith-Spark | first2 = Laura| last3 = Hanna | first3 = Jason| publisher = CNN| date = 24 March 2015| accessdate = 24 March 2015| url = http://edition.cnn.com/2015/03/24/europe/france-plane-crash/index.html}}</ref> German [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Germany)|Foreign Minister]] [[Frank-Walter Steinmeier]] flew over the crash site on 24 March, describing it as "a picture of horror".<ref name=BBC /> Merkel visited the recovery operations base at [[Seyne|Seyne-les-Alpes]] along with French Prime Minister Valls and Spanish [[Prime Minister of Spain|Prime Minister]] [[Mariano Rajoy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.english.rfi.fr/europe/20150325-hollande-merkel-rajoy-visit-germanwings-a320-crash-site-barcelona-dusseldorf |title=Hollande, Merkel, Rajoy visit Germanwings A320 crash site |publisher=[[Radio France Internationale]] |date=25 March 2015 |accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref>

===Commercial===

Several [[Germanwings]] flights were canceled on 24–25 March, which the pilots' union says was due to grief at the loss of their colleagues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.germanwings.com/en/information/current-information.html|title=Current information|publisher=Germanwings|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Distraught Germanwings pilots refuse to fly|publisher=CNN|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/03/25/news/companies/germanwings-crash-pilots/|date=25 March 2015}}</ref>

Lufthansa Chief Executive Carsten Spohr visited the crash location on 25 March, and afterwards said that this is "the darkest day for Lufthansa in its 60-year history".<ref name="ITVlufthansa25mar">{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2015-03-25/lufthansa-boss-says-past-hours-darkest-in-60-year-history/ |title=Lufthansa boss says past hours 'darkest in 60-year history' |publisher=ITV News |date=25 March 2015 |accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref>

Shortly after the crash, Germanwings changed its website and social media branding to [[greyscale]] images. Lufthansa, [[Swiss International Air Lines|Swiss]], and [[Austrian Airlines]] also did the same thing.

On 25 March, Germanwings retired the flight number 4U9525, changing it to 4U9441. The outbound flight number was also changed: from 4U9524 to 4U9440. The flight numbers for the later Düsseldorf to Barcelona flight remain unchanged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airlineroute.net/2015/03/24/4u-mar15/|title=germanwings Retires Flight Number 4U9525; New Flight Numbers from 25MAR15|publisher=airlineroute.net|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref>

When reporters asked Germanwings if another member of the flight crew must be present in the cockpit when one of the pilots leaves, they replied that the company has no such requirement, nor do [[EU OPS|European regulations]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2015/mar/26/germanwings-plane-crash-investigation-press-conference-live-updates-4u9525 |title=Germanwings crash: 'co-pilot's actions leave us speechless,' says airline – live updates |newspaper=The Guardian |date=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/26/us-france-crash-idUSKBN0MK2U020150326|title=Just one pilot in cockpit at time of French Alps crash: German prosecutor|date=26 March 2015|agency=Reuters|author=Jean-Francois Rosnoblet}}</ref> Aviation authorities in Canada and New Zealand have changed regulations,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/m/touch/news/story/1.3010494|title=Germanwings Flight 4U9525: Canadian airlines told to have 2 people in the cockpit|publisher=[[CBC News]]|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= Henry |last=Cooke |date=27 March 2015 |title= CAA changes cockpit policy following Germanwings crash |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/travel/news/67527128/air-nz-changes-cockpit-policy-following-germanwings-crash |publisher= Fairfax New Zealand |accessdate= 27 March 2015}}</ref> and many airlines have subsequently amended their policies to require at least two people to be on the flightdeck at all times during flight for safety reasons.<ref name=BBC32070570>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-europe-32070570|title=Germanwings crash latest updates (14:51)|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=BBC32075657>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-32075657|title=Budget airline Easyjet to require two crew on flightdeck|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>

